<font color="#FF0000">TO EDWARD</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jul 23  6:43:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Edward,<br><br>
Thanks for your thoughts. Your poem brings out a real issue. To consider the enemy as a fellow human being and worthy adversary is a part of the psychology with which I personally collide now and again as I continue to iterate through the whole experience.<br><br>
When I began to post on this site last Fall, I quickly came to the personal realization that nothing in my Vietnam War experience really fit. Instead of a seamless transition into and out of things, most of which were and continue to be troublesome, I felt I was confronted with a set of dominos on edge in a random pattern. Knock one over, and the rest fall out of control. A vortex is another visual analogy I find fitting for the whole experience.<br><br>
With increasing conviction, I have begun to realize that the reason why nothing seems to fit is that there are essential pieces missing. Actually, there are big holes. As I grapple with the aspects of my own humanity in this context, I feel that the process that put me into the situation was peculiarly avoiding and denying certain things that were needed to connect it all and at least leave things as a bad memory rather than the mess I continue to find residing in my head.<br><br>
I think it is time for me to read Shay's &quot;Achilles in Vietnam&quot;, once again. It probably doesn't surprise you that I have found a few of the missing pieces right here on this site.  
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


